        "This is the same as #25142 except for these differences:\n1. State modules are the salt minion's high level level interface to platforms and other systems.  They should leverage execution modules for low level work to keep state logic sanely orthogonal and distinct from exec logic.\n3. Additionally, the action of each function exposed to the user should be [idempotent](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Idempotence).\n5. The `return` statements in the functions exposed to the user should be in the form `{'name': name, 'changes': changes, 'result': result, 'comment: comment}` as described in [the documentation](http://docs.saltstack.com/en/latest/ref/states/writing.html#return-data).\n7. Because state modules run at a higher and more abstracted level than execution modules, they probably only need to be concerned with `MinionError` and `SaltInvocationError`.\n9. Each function exposed to the user needs to implement a test mode, when `__opts__['test'] == True`, in which it calculates the first order actions that would be taken by the state on the minion system given its current state.  Predicting higher order actions in a state run is a very nontrivial and potentially unsolvable problem, without [making changes](https://github.com/saltstack/salt/issues/24938) to the data states return.\n"
